---
title: "Organise by Description, Not Location"
type: atom
tags:
  - knowledge-management
---

I stopped creating a folder for everything. I describe what things are, not where they sit. A single note can belong to multiple contexts when the description is right.

This is the Zettelkasten insight applied to the AI age: categories are rigid, descriptions are flexible. A note about "enterprise security concerns around AI adoption" can live in any folder, but if its metadata and content describe it well, every search modality can find it regardless of where it sits.

Folders are locations. Metadata and links are descriptions. In a network, description wins.
